<DOC><DOCNO> AP890413-0217 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-13-89 1954EST</FILEID><FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     04-13 0489</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0502</SECOND><HEAD>Rain in Texas, New England and Plains; Mostly Fair and Mild Elsewhere</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Rain fell in Texas, New England and the northern Plains onThursday, and mild weather elsewhere in the nation brought water inanother form: flooding snowmelt.   Southeasterly winds spread moisture from the Gulf of Mexicoacross much of central and eastern Texas, where intense downpoursfell in some places. Golfball size hail was reported at BraunigLake, Texas.   A cold front pushed into western New England, bringing scatteredrainshowers. Snowshowers fell from parts of western Pennsylvaniainto south-central New York state. Bradford, Pa., received an inchof snow.   Rainshowers fell across eastern North Dakota and northwestMinnesota ahead of a cold front that was slowly sagging into theregion.   Mild temperatures were reported across much of the nation _ badnews for people living along swollen rivers.   The Red River continued to flood in eastern North Dakota andwestern Minnesota as melting snow raised its level to as high as 15feet above flood stage.   Minor lowland flooding also was reported along the Pearl Riverin southeast Louisiana and along the lower Ohio River.   Heavier rainfall during the six hours ending at 2 p.m. EDTincluded .56 inch at Dyess Air Force Base in Texas and about athird of an inch at Kingsville, Mineral Wells and Abilene, Texas.   Temperatures were in the 50s or 60s across much of the nation,but in the 40s across much of the Great Lakes and New England andin the 70s and 80s in parts of the South and Southwest.   A few cities recorded record low temperatures. The lows included28 degrees in Asheville, N.C., 36 in Huntsville, Ala., and 20 inMadison, Wis.   The low in the nation Thursday morning was 12 degrees atGunnison, Colo., and Marquette, Mich.   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 34degrees at Buffalo, N.Y., to 95 degrees at Palm Springs, Calif.   The National Weather Service forecast for Friday called forscattered rain from the Great Lakes through the middle MississippiValley, with widespread rainshowers and thunderstorms from theeastern parts of the southern Plains through the lower MississippiValley and the central Gulf Coast.   Scattered rain also was expected across the northern half ofMaine. The remainder of the nation was expected to have pleasant,mild weather.   High temperatures were expected to be in the 60s or 70s acrossmuch of the nation. Highs were forecast in the 50s from thenorthern High Plains through the northern Plains and the lowerGreat Lakes into much of New England; in the 40s from the upperMississippi Valley into the northern Great Lakes and acrossnorthern and coastal parts of New England; in the 80s across thesouthern half of Florida and the southern tip of Texas; and intothe 80s and 90s from Oregon through much of California into thedesert Southwest.</TEXT></DOC>